                "reputation": 19207,
                "display_name": "Hardy"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1400490394,
            "creation_date": 1400490394,
            "body": "<p>The short answer is: \"No, there is no way to manually add constraint violations\". <\/p>\n\n<p>To elaborate a little bit. As you say, all classes involved are interfaces. If you really think you want to do it, you could implement your custom <em>ConstraintViolationImpl<\/em>. However, I am wondering what your actual use case is? Why do you want to add a constraint violation without validation? As the answer <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/23727169/115835\">https://stackoverflow.com/a/23727169/115835<\/a> suggest, you could always go via a class level custom constraint. As part of <em>isValid<\/em> in your custom <em>ConstraintValidator<\/em> implementation, you get an <em>ConstraintValidatorContext<\/em> which will allow you to add additional constraint violations.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 23733812,
            "question_id": 23725707,
            "last_edit_date": 1495540409
        }
